In seven weeks I'm doing my first full Ironman. 

And honestly, it scares me.

That's exactly why I signed up.

The fastest growth of my life has never come from comfort. 

It comes from the growth zone - that edge where you're a little scared, doing things you've never done, finding out you're capable of more than you assumed.

The problem is the growth zone isn't where we naturally live. 

Left alone, most of us drift. We get comfortable. 

We coast on what already works. And I think drifting is the single biggest waste of human potential there is.

So the question I keep coming back to isn't "how hard should I push?" 

It's: what reliably pulls me into the growth zone, and keeps me there?

For me, it's endurance sports.

Right now I'm hitting distances I've never hit in my life - riding farther than I ever have, running more than I have in years.

And at times it sucks!

That's when I come back to this question of why I'm doing it in the first place.

The Ironman is what gets me in my growth zone.

And the best part?

Once you're in your growth zone in one area of your life, that same edge shows up in how you do everything.

But it doesn't have to be a triathlon.

For you it might be a creative project or even just swimming 25 meters if you're not a strong swimmer.

The activity isn't the point. 

Find the thing that gets you in your growth zone. Then keep going back.

What pulls you into your growth zone?